Their tone, mannerisms, and even personalities seem very different

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:31.020
meaning we can't get a handle on their character as well.

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:34.760
These characters are done a lot with Disney films recently

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:39.480
which is not bad, often times they work out fine and help serve the story or message

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:43.500
but when it's done this many times and with this many villains

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:45.080
not only does it start to get old

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:48.200
but we're kind of losing that connection to...well...

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:49.860
enjoying our dark side.

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:55.660
Nobody finds Hans, Bellwether, AUTO, or
Henry J. Waternoose cool villains

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:58.400
we don't enjoy watching them be evil, we just see them

00:09:58.400 --> 00:10:01.080
as nuisances that get in the way of our hero.

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:04.000
Now, they're good at being in the way and being roadblocks

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.120
but they're not charming, fun or charismatic like these villains are.

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:12.720
And that's because they weren't allowed to be villains throughout the majority of the film

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:15.580
so you can't enjoy them as much in that role.

00:10:15.580 --> 00:10:18.780
We don't get to see the devilish smirk of Frollo,

00:10:18.860 --> 00:10:20.920
the gratifying laugh of Jafar,

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:24.560
the evil just enjoying being evil of 
Night on Bald Mountain

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:27.540
that's what makes these villains so much fun.

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:31.880
But the fact remains these are stories that aren't supposed to belong to the villains

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:34.420
they're supposed to belong to heroes.

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:36.640
While the villains have to take a step backwards,

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:38.860
though, granted, a small step to be sure,

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:43.220
The heroes in Disney films are much more interesting and engaging than ever.

00:10:43.220 --> 00:10:49.420
Truthfully, these are the people we're supposed to learn from, supposed to look up to, supposed to want to be.

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:52.820
Their message and characteristics are 
much more interesting and complex

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:55.680
than that of dozens of older Disney films.

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:57.840
While these older movies are still classics,

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:01.080
and using both simplicity 
and complexity in the right places

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:03.300
Disney knows they need to evolve.

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:05.360
People change, rules change,

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:08.880
and people find different ways 
of getting those rules across.

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:11.160
One of the more interesting recent developments is that

00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:13.320
Disney doesn't always need villains.

00:11:13.540 --> 00:11:17.860
Sometimes it can just be a series of circumstances and conflicts that have to be overcome

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.600
And they don't always tie into 
just one individual causing it.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:25.100
The older villains used to be 
about battling the grand evil

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:27.320
and that not matter how threatening the danger

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:30.300
undying hope and strength can result in beating it.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:34.000
Modern day stories focus on 
a different kind of struggle.

00:11:34.460 --> 00:11:36.580
Struggles about identity, belonging,

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.860
seeing that things are not always as 
black and white as they seem.

00:11:39.980 --> 00:11:43.180
These are relevant issues and messages 
to get across today

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:47.360
and their antagonists have to reflect 
that in a way that best fits the story.

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:50.120
It's not meaning to tone down the fun of the villains,

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:52.900
it's just it's seen as what's needed at the moment.

00:11:53.260 --> 00:11:56.400
So, are Disney's animated villains 
as great as they used to be?

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:57.040
No.

00:11:57.040 --> 00:12:00.560
But there's a good and even admirable reason why.

00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:05.140
The same way Disney is trying to distance themselves from all their characters being too similar,

00:12:05.140 --> 00:12:08.560
the same can be said for changes 
that are needed for their villains.

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:11.880
The important lessons and creative ways 
they're trying to get across those lessons

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:14.960
don't always call for villains like in the old days.

00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:17.520
Would it be nice if some did?

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:21.320
Yes! And I hope they look into that
if for any other reason just variety.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:25.760
But Disney is on a hot streak because 
they know how to relate to people

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:28.340
and they know how to challenge and evolve.

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:31.420
Disney wants to be relevant and it wants to be helpful

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:34.940
and it will do so in the way that each time period needs.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:38.000
While the evilest of the evil seem old school now

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.540
maybe they'll come back in the near future.

00:12:40.540 --> 00:12:45.660
Because we always live in changing times and
people's focus and dilemmas change with those times.

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:49.860
Disney is always going to do it's best to 
follow the dreams and problems of people

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:52.900
and reflect them cinematically for all ages.

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:54.820
So, who knows what the future holds?

00:12:54.820 --> 00:12:57.600
Maybe villains will get better, 
maybe heroes will get better,

00:12:57.600 --> 00:12:59.000
maybe they'll both get better.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.960
Whatever happens, we still have a long line of 
badies who we'll look back on and smile

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:08.080
on how they always did their best to give us their worst.

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:14.240
I'm the Nostalgia Critic.
I remember it, so you don't have to.

